However if we still want to change `abc` into something else you can use method overriding. Here's how: 
```java
public class Try {  
    void abc() {} // old name for the function/method 'abcdfghijklmnopqrstuvwxyzABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefg'hilmlnjmnoPQLRTUVGH
    void ref(){ 
        abc(); // calling the method 'abcdfghijklmnopqrstuvwxyzABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefg'hilmlnjmnoPQLRTUVGH() here. This is called Method Overloading
    }  // end of ref method  
}//end class Try    
```      In the above code, `ref` calls a new version (or overload) of function/method named 'abc'. The actual name used in source file will depend on how you've defined and called it. If we call abc() directly from ref(), then method signature is same as before ie., void abc().

